And proceed to match those countries recent military commitment to Greenland, with a reduction in our commitment to NATO....maybe reduce a major base over there to the same size as the amount of men these countries just sent over to "defend" Greenland. Hey, if they think they are effectively defending Greenland right now against future Russian aggression, then the same levels of military support should be effective for Europe, right?

As far as Greenland, Trump doesn't need to get in a military conflict with them to control it. I believe we have a military base, in the northern part of that continent right now. All Trump has to do is extend the area the base controls to include everything above a certain latitude on the continent, then redirect those military resources from Europe to the defense of that area.

Trump doesn't need to engage any military to do this. He should just ignore their counter claims and any military activities they conduct. The only kind he should respond to is a military attack by them. 

If this happened (too stupid on their part) then a decisive military response on the continent would be justified.

This approach would be wise because of two factors.... presence and time.

First....it would give us an immediate effective military presence in the region.  (Nuclear armed hypersonic missiles are no joke.)

Second....it gives us time.

Greenland wouldn't switch to US hands overnight, even in a best case scenario. It takes years to develop anything meaningful, even when the process has started.

In a couple of years, Europe will be experiencing more inflation and unrest, so terms for any deal would favor us more. Who knows? By then they may have lost interest and Trump can deal with the Greenlanders directly?
